scripts.name: Run
scripts.script:
tell application "Xcode"
	activate
	delay 0.5
	tell application "System Events"
		tell process "Xcode"
			keystroke "r" using {command down}
		end tell
	end tell
end tell
scripts.description:
Run Project in Xcode

This automation instantly launches Xcode (if it’s not already active) and triggers the Run command, simulating the ⌘R keyboard shortcut. It’s a quick and reliable way to build and run your current project without manually switching to Xcode or touching your keyboard.

What it does:
	•	Activates the Xcode app
	•	Waits briefly to ensure it’s in focus
	•	Simulates ⌘R to start building and running the active scheme

Ideal for integrating into larger workflows or triggering from a companion app, voice assistant, or automation hub.

scripts.name: Stop
scripts.script:
tell application "Xcode"
	activate
	delay 0.5
end tell

tell application "System Events"
	tell process "Xcode"
	-- ⌘. to stop the current build or run
		keystroke "." using {command down}
	end tell
end tell
scripts.description:
Stop Build or Run in Xcode

This automation brings Xcode to the foreground and sends the Stop command, equivalent to pressing ⌘. (Command + Period). It’s perfect for quickly halting a running build, simulator session, or active debug process without switching contexts manually.

What it does:
	•	Activates the Xcode app
	•	Waits briefly to ensure it’s ready
	•	Simulates ⌘. to stop the current build or run session

Useful for canceling long builds or regaining control during testing workflows with ease.

scripts.name: Theme Switcher
scripts.script:
#!/bin/bash

# Check current appearance mode
current_mode=$(osascript -e 'tell application "System Events" to tell appearance preferences to get dark mode')

if [ "$current_mode" = "true" ]; then
  # Switch to Light mode
  osascript -e 'tell application "System Events" to tell appearance preferences to set dark mode to false'
  echo "Switched to Light Mode"
else
  # Switch to Dark mode
  osascript -e 'tell application "System Events" to tell appearance preferences to set dark mode to true'
  echo "Switched to Dark Mode"
fi
scripts.description:
Toggle macOS Appearance (Light/Dark Mode)

This automation script checks your current macOS system appearance (Light or Dark Mode) and toggles it to the opposite. It’s ideal for users who want quick control over system appearance — useful for scripting, productivity setups, or custom keyboard shortcuts.

What it does:

- Switches to the opposite mode
- Outputs a confirmation message to the terminal

Perfect for integrating into a larger automation tool or binding to a hotkey for instant theme switching.

scripts.description:

This automation allows you to quickly convert one or more .HEIC image files to .JPEG format using a script and macOS’s built-in tools. You simply select the images in Finder, run the script, and the converted images will appear in a folder on your Desktop.

scripts.name: MOV to MP4
scripts.script:
-- Get the selected file in Finder
tell application "Finder"
	set theSelection to selection
	if theSelection is {} then
		display dialog "Please select a video file in Finder." buttons {"OK"} default button 1
		return
	end if
	set inputFile to POSIX path of (item 1 of theSelection as alias)
end tell

-- Define output folder and file
set outputFolder to POSIX path of (path to desktop folder) & "MP4_Output/"
do shell script "mkdir -p " & quoted form of outputFolder

-- Extract filename and prepare output path
do shell script "/usr/bin/basename " & quoted form of inputFile & " .mov"
set baseName to the result
set outputFile to outputFolder & baseName & ".mp4"

-- Run FFmpeg in Terminal with progress
tell application "Terminal"
	activate
	do script "ffmpeg -i " & quoted form of inputFile & " -c:v libx264 -c:a aac -vf format=yuv420p -movflags +faststart " & quoted form of outputFile
end tell
scripts.description: This macOS automation streamlines the process of converting .mov video files to .mp4 format using FFmpeg. Simply select a video file in Finder, run the automation, and it will automatically create a folder on your Desktop (MP4_Output) to store the converted file. The conversion uses efficient encoding settings for wide compatibility and fast playback (libx264, aac, yuv420p, and +faststart). Progress is shown in Terminal, giving you real-time feedback. Ideal for batch processing video clips or preparing media for web and mobile use.

	set volume with output muted
else

end if

scripts.name: Empty Trash
scripts.description: Quickly and securely empty your Mac’s Trash with a single automated action. This tool helps you reclaim disk space and keep your system tidy—no need to open Finder or confirm multiple prompts. Ideal for maintaining a clean workspace as part of your regular cleanup or shutdown routine.
scripts.script:
display dialog "Are you sure you want to empty the Trash?" buttons {"Cancel", "Empty Trash"} default button "Cancel" with icon caution
if button returned of the result is "Empty Trash" then
	tell application "Finder"
		if (count of items in trash) > 0 then
			empty the trash
		end if
	end tell
end if

scripts.description: Saves newly created presentation. It automatically enters the name and saves it to desktop.

-- Make sure PowerPoint is frontmost
tell application "System Events"
	tell process "Microsoft PowerPoint"
		set frontmost to true
		delay 0.5

		-- Open Save As dialog (Cmd + Shift + S)
		keystroke "S" using {command down, shift down}

		-- Type file name

		delay 0.5

		-- Confirm Save

	end tell

scripts.description: Automatically apply your custom watermark to images in Photoshop 2025 with a single action. This automation opens your files, inserts a predefined watermark (text or image), positions it precisely (e.g., bottom-right corner), adjusts opacity for subtle branding, and saves the result—ready for publishing or sharing. Perfect for photographers, designers, and content creators who want to protect their work and maintain a consistent visual identity without repetitive manual steps.
scripts.name: Add Watermark
scripts.script:
set watermarkText to "© YourName 2025"
set watermarkPercentage to 5 -- Percentage of the image width

tell application "Adobe Photoshop 2025"
    activate
    set docRef to current document
    tell docRef
        -- Calculate watermark size as a percentage of the image width
        set watermarkSize to (docRef's width * watermarkPercentage) / 100
        
        make new art layer with properties {kind:text layer}
        set contents of text object of current layer to watermarkText
        set position of text object of current layer to {50, docRef's height - 50}
        set size of text object of current layer to watermarkSize
        set opacity of current layer to 50
    end tell
end tell

scripts.description: Quickly flatten all layers in your Photoshop 2025 project with a single automated action. This tool merges all visible layers into one, preserving the final visual result while simplifying the file structure—ideal for preparing images for export, reducing file size, or finalizing edits. Eliminate the hassle of manual layer merging and streamline your workflow with one click.
scripts.name: Flatten All
scripts.script:
set exportFolder to choose folder with prompt "Choose folder to save flattened copies:"

tell application "Adobe Photoshop 2025"
	activate
	repeat with docRef in documents
		tell docRef
			flatten
			set exportName to name
			set exportPath to (exportFolder as text) & "flat-" & exportName
			set jpegOptions to {class:JPEG save options, quality:10}
			save in file exportPath as JPEG with options jpegOptions
		end tell
	end repeat
end tell

scripts.description: Automatically create a timestamped backup of your current Photoshop 2025 project with this automation. It saves a duplicate of your working file to a designated backup folder, preserving your progress without interrupting your workflow. Ideal for version control, experimentation, and peace of mind—never lose a key stage of your creative process again.
scripts.name: Backup File
scripts.script:
set backupFolder to choose folder with prompt "Select backup folder for all open PSDs:"

tell application "Adobe Photoshop 2025"
	activate
	repeat with docRef in documents
		tell docRef
			set docName to name
			if docName does not end with ".psd" then set docName to docName & ".psd"
			set savePath to backupFolder as text & "backup-" & docName
			save in file savePath as Photoshop format
		end tell
	end repeat
end tell

scripts.description: Instantly rotate your Photoshop 2025 canvas by 90 degrees clockwise with this automation.
